content.description: Thin and vertical climbing on featured rock. Good quality

One of the first things anyone notices when they turn that final agonizing corner up the dam and face the mountain is a massive black split between two of the largest boulders in sight. Think of it as the Big Grunt of Lake Ramona.
content.location:
Top of the hill.

The anchor is easily accessible by walking around back and stemming between the boulders. Some may choose to have a belay for setting up the anchor.

content.description: Stand start from the rock below, sharp crimps and no feet then desperately huck a couple times for small holds then easy slab... like so many climbs in San Diego.  it's worth doing if you're playing the Waiting Game while others are scumming up the off-width.
content.location: The short boulder below Waking Up the Giants with a very striking pattern of holds

content.description: Sit start on the ledge and jug undercling and make powerful moves on bad slopers. Temp dependent.
content.location: On the Summit Ridge, west of the main summit. Walk past Cataclysm and head downhill to the large long boulder with Avocado Bravado. This boulder is just west.

content.description: Sit start with right hand low on the arete and left hand on an undercling. Make some cool, powerful moves up the steep arete to an easy top out. Great movement up a nice feature! The stand start is also fun and goes at about V2.
content.location: The left arete of the Signal Fire boulder.

content.description: Very worthwhile slab climbing on this tall, featured face.  Main climb is far right.  I had to pull some flakes at the beginning but the whole face is very solid now. Easier climbs are to the left on the face.
content.location: In between the towers, same boulder as Sanctum Arete

content.description: A clean hand and finger crack with some face holds.  This is a nice little summit.
content.protection: Fingers/hands.  There is a bolt on top.
content.location: The "Two Towers" are an area landmark.  This is on the east face of the west tower.

content.description: Follow a seam with good holds and decent feet for about 15 feet or so. From there, move slightly to the right to a nice juggy hold. Top out up and to the right, moving out onto the face. It’s possible to continue following the seam until it peters out, but the rock quality becomes pretty questionable and would need to be cleaned up.
content.location: Behind the Aerial Chariot boulder, if approaching Granite Geek you’ll pass right on by it.

content.description:
A steep problem in high quality rock. It's short but has a nice flowing sequence. Fun and well worth doing.

Video:

youtu.be/6fLvrh9r70A
content.location: 50 yards west of the highest rock pile is a large split boulder with a tree next to it. The problem is just below this boulder, facing west.

content.description: Tall face climb with small holds on perfect, orange granite. Bad landing. Good thing it’s easy. Finishes with an exciting mantle.

A sick problem up a very obvious feature perched on the Summit Ridge.

Start on a right hand sidepull and left on a crimp. Reach up to the flake hold with a jug foot. Get situated on the flake, move right to a small crimp and make a spicy last move to a jug over the lip.
content.protection: Pads. Landing is a bit funky
content.location: On the Summit Ridge, east of Cataclysm Arete

content.description:
Start up nice edges and work into the flared chimney/hand crack, then scooch your way up to the top.

There's another problem on the south side of the boulder, following another strange hand/fist crack in a flared chimney.
content.location: Formed by the boulder leaning against the East Summit Tower. Climbs the east side.

content.description:
A uniquely positioned boulder offers a beautiful overhanging arete with good holds. The moves are fairly straight forward and the slab topout adds a little extra jaw-clenching excitement. This problem has plenty of shade between the giant towers and an oak tree... perfect refuge for a hot day.

Possible sit start would be vary hard compression*
Start low with hands on some rad small pockets on either side of the boulder. Make a couple hard slap moves and finish on Sanctum Arete.
content.location: Low start to Sanctum Arete.

content.description: Quality slab problem on bullet rock. Start matched on slopey dimples, stand up and right to a sloper scoop, and mantle up to a small crimp on the lip.
content.location: Directly north of Cataclysm.

content.description:
Start on two good slopers with a right heel hook and mantle over to the arete. Stand up to reach the lip. Nice line with a bad landing.

There are a bunch of nice slabs around the other side of the arete as well (5.9 - 5.10).
content.location: Just east of the East Summit Tower (Granite Geek). Climbs the boulder with the defined arete.

content.description: The short dimpled face with cool holds on solid rock.
content.location: Just south of the two towers.  The problem faces southwest.

content.description: Another fun, featured face.
content.location: Behind AM and Aerial Chariot

content.description: At first glance, this problem looks hard but there's this thin flake that lets you cruise to the top in very few moves. Really fun for an easy climb. Worth doing. Same boulder as Ante Meridiem
Classic A-frame invert problem on great rock! Start by scooting back into your new favorite hole, get a good hand jam, and invert out the south side of the boulder. Work your feet up and pivot.
content.location: Small cluster of boulders just east of the East Summit Tower (Granite Geek).

content.description:
This route starts off with a height dependent boulder problem on small crimps, then moves into classic face climbing on awesome features. The true grade may be something like 12a/d. Some of the holds are delicate, be careful with how you grab them.

1 star boulder problem leads into a 4 star finish...so if you aren't feeling the heinous start, it's worth pulling up to climb the classic 5.10+ finish.
content.protection: TR bolts, extend with a long sling.
content.location: To the left of Granite Geek.

content.description:
A great, funky problem up a very obvious feature. Start off the spike and pull onto subtle, slopey holds and a small right foot edge. Make your way up some desperate slopers before hitting the jug scoop. Mantle in and walk up to the lip.

If you're tall you may be able to reach the jug scoop from the right foot, making it much easier.
content.location: Just south of the Two Towers, on the north facing scoop feature.

content.description: I felt compelled to add this simply because of the beauty of this rock, which resembles the whale (Monstro) from Pinocchio.

Currently the hardest pure press at LR. Start in the middle of the shelf with a low foot on the jug. Press it out on the grippy slopers.

There is a slightly easier variation to the left, on the corner of the boulder, called The Sickness.

This would be 5.12- at Woodson. Those guys were beasts. But it is probably closer to V7/8 in more modern areas. Get psyched!
content.location: East of the Two Towers, down in the gully.

content.description: A fun and techy route up a nice orange face.
content.protection: Two TR bolts, accessed by leading up the Summit Lieback.
content.location: South face of Granite Geek Tower.

content.description: A clean arete lieback on great rock. Crux is establishing yourself on the wall.
content.location: Just east of the Granite Geek Tower.

content.description:
This is a special one.

Sent on Father's Day 2019, with my dad belaying.

Not your average splitter crack climb…incredibly varied movement, using a mix of liebacking, tips locks, crimps and even a kneebar. It’s hard right off the ground, with an intricate sequence through the steepest section of the route. The difficulties don’t let up until a "rest" about halfway up. Then there is one more cruxy section, followed by pumpy 5.10+ fingers to the top. Amazing sequences.

One of San Diego's best.
content.protection: Thin, but good. Doubles from Green C3 to Red C3, an extra 0.2 and 0.3 X4. 1 bolt and a 0.3 X4/C4 for the anchor.
content.location: On the west face of the Summit Towers...can't miss it. It takes about an hour and 10 minutes to get to the base of this route from the car.

content.description:
One of the hard cracks of the hill. Kind of like a reverse Starving in Stereo. Starts with some thin crack moves, until it pinches down to crimpy liebacking. Delicate finish.

Still awaiting a lead ascent...
content.location: Just west of the Summit, two big boulders stacked on top of each other.

content.description: A clean, offset and slanting splitter, forming a super juggy lieback with great gear. Really fun climbing on this one.
content.location: The west face of the east summit tower.

content.description:
A short overhang on perfect holds, begging to be climbed. Sit start over left, matched on a good edge. Move right to a nice crimp, then fire to the sloper lip and mantle.

This was one of the first hard looking problems we spotted up on the hill 3 years ago.
content.location: Tucked between the two Summit Towers

content.description: SDS on perfect sidepulls and move up and right on small crimps, aiming for a jug sidepull. Finish straight up the face. The huge jugs over right are a bit sketchy, best to avoid them.
content.location: North of Cataclysm, on the backside of the boulder with a big scoop.

content.description: Sit start down and left of Hobo Cave, matched on a cool pinch.  Bust a hard move right into the start of Hobo Cave, then lock off to a hold in the middle of the face.  Move right and finish up Hobo Cave.  Really cool moves and holds, but a little grainy.
content.location: Same boulder as Hobo Cave.

content.description: This shorter climb follows a gently overhanging face with good but still somehow difficult holds to a big throw for the top. Starts in the cave as a sit start. Will get a third star once the start cleans up a bit.
This crack starts out with very powerful undercling moves and precision footwork then leads to delicate and anxious face climbing up a tall series of intricate holds.  It's tenacious.
content.location:
East Summit Tower

Lead

Lieback Crack

to access anchor.

content.description:
A nice crimp line with a crux start and an easier but committing finish.

There is an obvious bucket above the lip that looks sketchy. I wasn’t able to break it off but I’d avoid it, there are jugs on either side of it.
content.protection: Pad/spotter. Be prepared to either down climb Aerial Chariot to the jug and drop off, or bring a rope and buddy rappel over the top.
content.location: To the left of Aerial Chariot. Stand start on a juggy right hand sidepull and a left crimp.

content.description:
Start with your left hand in a waist high undercling slot, and your right hand on a jug at about head height on the arete. High step into a left hand/foot match, lock off the right and make a big reach up with the left hand to a credit card thin crimp. Figure out how to stay on as you bring your hips in and get a good high right foot. Then, keep it tight as you reach over with your right hand to a good, in-cut 1/2 pad sidepull. Once you’ve got it, match hands (playing the piano may be required) and reach out and to the right to a good sidepull. Another reach directly overhead with your left leads to another good edge. Hike your feet up, lock off the left and reach up to one more crimpy edge before it’s cruiser jugs to the top.

When viewing the boulder from the East it looks like a half-buried skull, hence the name.
content.protection: A couple of pads and a good spot.
content.location: Located on the right side of the South face of the Mega boulder, just downhill from Sunbeam. Avocado Bravado sits on the opposite end of the boulder.

content.description: Start on the obvious crimp for the right hand in the ripples and a three finger scoop for the left, pull onto bad feet and slap slopers straight up. Round.
content.location: East of the Granite Geek Tower in the gully.

content.description: Climb good sidepull scoops up the Eye. Awesome feature.
content.location: Located on the large chimney boulder west of the main Summit.

content.description:
A set of cracks separated by a sloping terrace, while unremarkable on their own, make for a fun lap when linked together.

Top out the first crack, and choose from a left or a right wide crack in opposing dihedrals on the 2nd floor terrace. Both go at about the same grade. Hands, fists, handstacks and/or a little stemming.
content.location: Around the corner from Waking the Giants.

content.description: Mantle the small sloper protruding from the lip.
content.location: Just to the right of Cwank 1.

content.description: A nice mantle on a cool scoop.
content.location: Just east of the Summit Towers. Cluster of small boulders.

content.description:
Tall, technical slab with not-so-inspiring holds.

It would get another star if it weren't for the many flakes I pulled off.
content.location: Right beneath Ante Meridiem and Ye Be Warned

content.description: At some point in time, this massive boulder cleaved perfectly in half, leaving a completely featureless face and a small diving board feature on top. This incredible climb follows the right side of the left arête of the boulder. 20 feet of perfect, balancy arête liebacking with positive holds and nonexistent feet! Try not to use the diving board as a hold, or take caution if you do.
content.location: This is an easy one to spot from the hike in. Along the summit ridgeline, look for the shadow cast by the diving board. 33° 1'56.00"N, 117° 0'0.24"W

content.description: The left side of the Cataclysm Arete offers another classic problem on excellent rock, this one being steeper and more powerful than the right side. Slap up the arete with off balance moves and bad feet down low, and easing up towards the top. Do it again and again!
content.location: This is an easy one to spot from the hike in. Along the summit ridgeline, look for the shadow cast by the diving board. 33° 1'56.00"N, 117° 0'0.24"W.

content.description: Fun slab climb. Starting from the left, move onto the face and make some high-steps between the horizontal rails. Good topout. Be careful of some of the small foot chips...
content.location: Just east of the large boulder that holds Avocado Bravado.

content.description: Sit start in the cool hueco feature and traverse up and left on good edges.
content.location: Just west of the large boulder that hosts Avocado Bravado.

content.description:
Sit start on a low rail and follow it up and right to slab top-out

The name came from my personal epic through the avocado orchard on my bike (with permission).  I DO NOT recommend it.

On one of the largest, prominant boulders on the hill there’s a striking line that follows a diagonal sloped rail that takes you high off the deck. The climb is technical and requires some confidence as a fall could be consequential. It’s absolutely a must-do if you’re comfortable with this grade.

As the Crow Flies is a saying derived from an ancient Nordic sea navigation method.
content.location: Look for the giant “sail” looking boulder in the shade of an oak tree. The climb is on the west side.

content.description:
Perched up on the summit of the mountain, more than 3 miles from the trailhead, sits one of the most proud faces of a boulder in the county. This east-facing boulder fractured eons ago, leaving just enough to be climbed and nothing more. It's perfect, if you ask me. Named in respect to all we do in the A.M. as climbers for a full day on the rock.

True grade is the vague B1 (reach dependent)
content.location:
Just east of the enormous boulder that resembles a spinnaker sail... just below

Ye Be Warned

and

Aerial Chariot

.

content.description: As the name suggests, this ascends directly up the beautifully featured face from the start of Aerial Chariot, staying off of the incut side-pull rail over to the left (that’s for Aerial Chariot). The crux involves either a dead point to a bad sloping crimp, or a big dynamic move (exciting, considering the position) to a slopey pinch/knob. The climbing eases substantially from there, as you follow jugs to the same finish as Aerial Chariot.
content.location: Aerial Chariot Boulder

content.description: This is an excellent boulder problem on cool, featured rock, going up the exposed tower sitting on top of Ye Be Warned. Sit start down and right with hands on a finger bucket and a crimp. Traverse up and left with some powerful moves on awesome crimps, then move straight up through an arching gaston/sidepull feature to a bucket. Easy climbing to the top.
content.location: This problem is on the south face of the obvious tower sitting on top of Ye Be Warned. To get down, either down climb to the jug and jump off, or rap off if you have a rope.  33° 1'56.80"N, 116°59'54.26"W
